The losers remain challengers.
HARARE: Before this month's presidential elections, I was convinced that irregularities in the elections would have serious consequences both in Zimbabwe and throughout southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe did not receive them.
Instead, they received terror.
Over the two years that led to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats by the party of Robert Mugabe, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
The ZANU terrorism is the responsibility of the criminal elements among the veterans from Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, the government militias, and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
The result of intimidation and violence was that my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), failed to reach a significant portion of the electorate, particularly in rural areas.
In addition, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, has effectively disempowered hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Since there were not enough polling stations overall, in my opinion, more than 360,000 people stood in line in Harare and Chitungwiza alone, unable to cast their ballots into the ballot boxes.
I continue to question the legitimacy of the election results because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from deploying election observers at 52% of rural polling stations.
Towards the end of the vote, our party's observers were missing at 6 out of 10 polling stations in the countryside.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to assert their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all polling stations that were controlled exclusively by ZANU supporters.
In our previous investigations, even in this early stage, a pattern has emerged: in these polling stations, most of the votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the results of the presidential elections, in which the current president Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is considered illegitimate in their eyes.
The people of Zimbabwe had their right to freely and democratically elect a president of their choice taken away.
The struggle over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined, and it is deserved that this be acknowledged.
Maybe it's not too late for that yet.
I am writing this text in sorrow, for Mugabe's regime still ignores the will of the people.
Whatever happens, I will stand by the people as a loyal servant and walk the path with them to the end.
Possibly, the government wants to arrest me.
I was also arrested for high treason before the elections.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the will of the people, to reclaim its rights and power.
It is up to us to carry out a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overcome us.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be willing to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen fear the people, and we have heard that they will do anything to kill the messenger.
Should it come to that, I ask the people of Zimbabwe only to remain strong and to see our shared endeavor through to the end.
There are many heroes in the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who could not be driven away.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voices must be heard around the world.
We have walked a very rocky path together to achieve a democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people have rarely had to endure such violence and yet have managed to retain kindness and exuberance.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
You cannot just leave these elections as they are, but you must also not fall for Mugabe's provocations and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe desire change in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not alone.
We know that in all of Africa, fraud occurs during elections.
In most African countries, irregularities, fraud, and deception in elections seem to be the norm.
In Africa, there is always some crisis due to elections somewhere.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it is time to grant people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in the hour of their greatest need.
I swear not to leave it.
